05889nam a22008895i 9780228007562DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280075627 a10.1515/97802280075622doi  a(DE-B1597)657758  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD9502.A2bI52 2021 7aTEC0560002bisacsh04a333.7922300aIn a New Light :bHistories of Women and Energy /ced. by R.W. Sandwell, Abigail Harrison Moore. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b14 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tIntroduction -- tChanging the Plot: Including Women in Energy History (and Explaining Why They Were Missing) -- tFinding Women in the History of Lighting: Candles in the English Home, 1815–1910 -- tWomen, Fear, and Fossil Fuels -- tAgency, Ambivalence, and the Women’s Guide to Powering Up the Home in England, 1870–1895 -- tWomen in Energy Engineering: Changing Roles and Gender Contexts in Britain, 1890–1934 -- tBrown Bread and Washing Machines: Nostalgia and Perspective in Irish Women’s Experiences of Rural Electrification -- tComplex Agency in the Great Acceleration: Women and Energy in the Ruhr Area after 1945 -- tAnthropocene Women: Energy, Agency, and the Home in Twentieth-Century Britain -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early 1970s, a German study estimated that women expended as many calories cleaning their coal-mining husbands' work clothes as their husbands did working below ground, arguably making the home as much a site of industrialized work as factories and mines. But while energy studies are beginning to acknowledge the importance of social and historical contexts and to produce more inclusive histories of the unprecedented energy transitions that powered industrialization, women have remained notably absent from these accounts.In a New Light explores the vital place of women in the shift to fossil fuels that spurred the Industrial Revolution, illuminating the variety of ways in which gender and energy intersected in women's lives in nineteenth- and twentieth-century Europe and North America. From their labour in the home, where they managed the adoption of new energy sources, to their work as educators in electrical housecraft and their protests against the effects of industrialization, women took on active roles to influence energy decisions.Together these essays deepen our understanding of the significance of gender in the history of energy, and of energy transitions in the history of women and gender. By foregrounding women's energetic labours and concerns, the authors shed new light on energy use in the past and provide important insights as societies move towards a carbon-neutral future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnergy consumptionxHistoryy19th century. 0aEnergy consumptionxHistoryy20th century. 0aEnergy consumptionxSocial aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aEnergy consumptionxSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aHome economicsxHistoryy19th century. 0aHome economicsxHistoryy20th century. 0aHouseholdsxEnergy consumptionxHistoryy19th century. 0aHouseholdsxEnergy consumptionxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aTechnology & Engineering / History.2bisacsh  aBritish.  aCanadian.  aIrish.  acandles.  ademonstrators.  adomestic energy.  aelectricity.  aenergy.  aengineers.  afear.  afuture energy choices.  agas.  aheat.  ahistory home.  alight.  aoil.  asocial history.  